> Explicit iterators are really only noise for the &quot;natural&quot; iterator, i.e. in order iteration over an array.<p>Not really, they are really noise in a lot of situations. Right now, I can only think of one case where they are necessary: lazy traversal. Either the collection is huge or each element is expensive to materialize, so you want to do that one at a time. Iterators are perfect for this.<p>They are unnecessary in all other cases. For example, for your (key, value) example:<p><pre><code>    for (Entry<String, String> entry: map.entrySet()) { ... }
</code></pre>
Go exposes too many implementation details to my taste.

A notable use of this pattern is bufio.Scanner: <a href="http://golang.org/pkg/bufio/#Scanner" rel="nofollow">http://golang.org/pkg/bufio/#Scanner</a><p>An example, scanning lines from standard input:<p><pre><code>    s := bufio.NewScanner(os.Stdin)
    for s.Scan() {
        fmt.Println(s.Text()) 
    }
    if err := s.Err(); err != nil {
        fmt.Fprintln(os.Stderr, &quot;reading standard input:&quot;, err)
    }</code></pre>
